11/Feb/21 2:58 PM;michaelak;So, after some investigation I found some points of interest:
 # Literally, there isn't any info, which type of timestamp must be used in RPM metadata. According to [http://createrepo.baseurl.org/] - "FIXME The specification needs better and more current documentation and needs to be included here. :)", LOL. But, looks like, that just a tradition, that all timestamps in RPM should be UNIX timestamp e.g. seconds from Epoch.
 #  Our class representation of files use milliseconds for our timestamps like so:
{code:java}
this.created = System.currentTimeMillis();
this.lastModified = this.created;
{code}
Which means, that we are working with file object attributes as timestamp with milliseconds.

 # The lastModified field takes the value from _ItemInfo_ without any changes. So, that explains, why only one field in _primary.xml_ and widely in rpm metadata contains timestamp with milliseconds - only it comes from the file info. It's need just to convert milliseconds to seconds.

* In addition, if an RPM package was already deployed before the current fix, and nothing was deployed or reindex didn't ran - we fallback to the cached version, but we will still take the right timestamp value in seconds.

