We recently had some database issues that caused errors in the applications log looking like this:
{code:java}
Failed to move from src=/firmware-releases-cfp/.tmp/release/2057d039210f40459d55b2c588b9c417 to target=/firmware-releases-cfp/release/product/1.40/1.40.4_final: Failed to acquire lock for: category: 'firmware-releases-cfp' key: 'release/product/1.40/1.40.4_final/PTZ/visca' owner: 'node-se-isitartifact02x' thread id: '88' thread name: 'http-nio-8081-exec-32': Failed to acquire lock for: category: 'firmware-releases-cfp' key: 'release/product/1.40/1.40.4_final/PTZ/visca' owner: 'node-se-isitartifact02x' thread id: '88' thread name: 'http-nio-8081-exec-32'
{code}
 

These errors caused the "api/move" request to fail as expected. But, the content was partially moved which was not at all expected. I would *not* expect a failed REST API request to make any changes to the database, certainly not partial changes.

 

I would expect Artifactory to do everything it needs within one API request in one database transaction. And if the request fails, for any reason, the transaction is rolled back and no changes are committed to the database.

In some cases, users do not perform an in-place upgrade, instead, they use provisioning tools(e.g. Terraform) to replace an existing node with a new node with a higher version. When a user has dozens or hundreds of licenses/bucket licenses, for obvious reasons he/she will not copy over single license files from filesystem to Terraform, as it can become a tedious work to manage licenses in Terraform when they get expired/renewed/replaced, etc. In this case, when replacing an existing node with new node with higher version it fails to upgrade due to missing licenses at the filesystem level, and as a result, the new node/service becomes unavailable. Adding the licenses through the UI of the node, or through JFrog Mission Control (JFMC) is not possible either as the service of the node is unavailable. 

 

{{Steps to reproduce:}}

{{1. Installed Artifactory HA v7.3.2 with single node pointing to external DB(PostgreSQL)}}
 {{2. Installed JFMC v4.4.0, configured it with Artifactory v7.3.2, added bucket license.}}
 {{3. Shut down Artifactory HA, and JFMC}}
 {{4. Copied the entire $Artifactory_Home/etc directory into /tmp/ (except the artifactory.cluster.license. file, since it is already in the database)}}
 {{5. Uninstalled completely Artifactory v7.3.2, and removed all leftover directories like /var/opt/jfrog & /opt/jfrog}}
 {{6. Installed new Artifactory v7.4.3}}
 {{7. Copied over the entire /tmp/etc to $Artifactory_Home/etc}}
 {{8. Downloaded JDBC driver into $Artifactory_Home/tomcat/lib}}
 {{9. Started Artifactory v7.4.3}}

 

 

{{Ran into this error:}}

{{2020-06-24T03:52:07.380Z [jfrt ] [WARN ] [1c4656c357810f4d] [o.a.a.ConverterBlockerImpl:68 ] [ocalhost-startStop-2] - No valid installed license found. Blocking conversion}}
 {{2020-06-24T03:52:07.381Z [jfrt ] [ERROR] [1c4656c357810f4d] [.a.c.ConvertersManagerImpl:215] [ocalhost-startStop-2] - Conversion failed. You should analyze the error and retry launching Artifactory. Error is: Converter can't run since no matching license found, please add new license}}
 {{2020-06-24T03:52:07.382Z [jfrt ] [ERROR] [1c4656c357810f4d] [tifactoryHomeConfigListener:59] [ocalhost-startStop-2] - Failed initializing Home. Converter can't run since no matching license found, please add new license}}
 {{2020-06-24T03:52:07.383Z [jfrt ] [ERROR] [1c4656c357810f4d] [actoryContextConfigListener:82] [ocalhost-startStop-2] - Failed initializing Artifactory context: Artifactory home not initialized.}}

 

 

I believe the new node should be able to pull the Artifactory license from the database during the initial startup, or at least let the new node to start so that the user can add the license from the UI/JFMC.

For the Helm Charts that are provided to install Artifactory on k8s, it would be nice to be able to just specify global.storageClass and have it apply to both Artifactory and Postgresql. Right now, only Postgresql honors it and you have to specify it a different place for artifactory file storage:
  
 {{**}}
{code:java}
artifactory:
 persistence:
 storageClassName: vmfs{code}
{{**}}
  
 Ideally, if you set:
  
 {{**}}
{code:java}
global:
storageClass: "vmfs"{code}
{{**}}
  
 It would apply to everything that the Artifactory chart installs.

Artifactory 7 does not have a way to configure the max header size for the frontend service. As a result, it seems to get the default header size, which is 8k for the version node that is in Artifactory 7.2.1 (node v10.16.3).

There are ways to configure tomcat to allow larger headers via the system.yaml, but there isn't a way to configure frontend. To work around this, I edited /opt/jfrog/artifactory/app/bin/artifactoryCommon.sh's node startup command to include the flag, which is a hacky way to force the header change on restart. 
{code:java}
initNode() {
    export NODE="${JF_PRODUCT_HOME}/app/third-party/node/bin/node --max-http-header-size 16384"
    # export NODE="${JF_PRODUCT_HOME}/app/third-party/node/bin/node"
    export NODE_ENV=PRODUCTION #TODO (matank): should be removed after JFUI-1372 will be resolved
}
{code}
Having a way to configure the max header size for all microservices would be very useful.

