When calling Artifactory's API to get an artifact's metadata, example:
 {{[https://artifactory.example.com/api/storage/maven-releases/com/example/example-service/1.0.0/example-service-1.0.0.war?properties]}}

and the {{properties}} map for this given artifact is empty, it returns an HTTP 404 response with the following JSON:
{code:json}
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "status": 404,
      "message": "No properties could be found."
    }
  ]
}
{code}
instead of HTTP 200 with an empty {{properties}} map:
{code:json}
{
  "properties": {
  },
  "uri": "https://artifactory.example.com/api/storage/maven-releases/com/example/example-service/1.0.0/example-service-1.0.0.war?properties"
}
{code}
Problem:
 - returning an HTTP 404 is not desirable here as it is not the appropriate API response, and it creates issues with HTTP clients trying to interact with the API thinking that the HTTP "resource" is missing (404) when in fact it is not missing, it is simply empty (the map being empty)

Solution:
 - return HTTP 200 as the {{properties}} map is in fact considered "empty", not "missing"

Note:
 - there is a definite distinct between a resource being "missing" vs it being "empty"
 - this is especially important because of the following 2 use cases:
 -- _valid_ API call:
 --- [https://artifactory.example.com/api/storage/maven-releases/com/example/example-service/1.0.0/example-service-1.0.0.war?properties]
 -- _invalid_ API call:
 --- [https://artifactory.example.com/api/storage/maven-releases/com/example/example-service/1.0.0/example-service-1.0.0.war?doesNotExist]
 - both of these use cases return the same type of 404 JSON, which is incorrect API behaviour, because for the first use case it would be much more appropriate to return an HTTP 200 with an empty {{properties}} map, while in the second use case it is in fact a "missing" resource (it does not exist)

