19/Nov/20 10:40 PM;kyle.schmid@teradata.com;After some discussion with JFrog support, I think our original assumption is wrong. AWS S3 will rate limit IOPS per prefix, and if we move all the files into the root, it will all be under the prefix of "/". Files are not part of the prefix, so if you put files in the root of the bucket, or even just under /filestore you are limiting your self  to a single prefix. 

The following first 10 mins of this video explains prefixes better than I can. 
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=54AhwfME6wI

For example:
{noformat}
1. <bucket name>/<file name> - This will put everything under the root directory and you will only have a single prefix. {noformat}
{noformat}
2. <bucket name>/filestore/<file name> - This will put everything under the /filestore directory and you will only have a single prefix. {noformat}
{noformat}
3. <bucket name>/filestore/<00 - ff>/<filename> - This will create a different prefix for /fiestore/00, /filestore/01, /filestore/02, ect... that means you will have 256 different prefixes and at the min of 3500 IOPS pre prefix you will get 896,000 IOPS per sec. {noformat}

